a training manual

00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:06.940
for new employees
and new analysts.

00:08:06.940 --> 00:08:10.370
So I opened the training
manual and looked it through.

00:08:10.370 --> 00:08:12.630
I actually found my answer.

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:16.150
So actually, at Morgan Stanley
this is not called vega,

00:08:16.150 --> 00:08:17.760
it's called kappa.

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:20.030
So now, I remember
to call it kappa.

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:21.980
Kappa is actually
a Greek letter.

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:25.590
So further, I look
on the same page

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:29.750
there was actually a
footnote, which I copied down.

00:08:29.750 --> 00:08:39.659
So the footnote about why it's
called kappa at Morgan Stanley.

00:08:39.659 --> 00:08:43.244
Kappa is also called vega
by some uneducated traders

00:08:43.244 --> 00:08:45.099
at the Salomon Brothers.

00:08:45.099 --> 00:08:46.140
That's where I came from.

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:47.850
I just joined.

00:08:47.850 --> 00:08:50.800
They have mistaken
vega as a Greek letter

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:52.080
after gambling at Vegas.

00:08:55.370 --> 00:08:58.510
So anyway, so that
was my first day.

00:08:58.510 --> 00:09:02.640
So obviously, I learned
how to call kappa

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:05.580
very quickly, because I
came from Salomon Brothers.

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:09.790
And I called it kappa
in the last 17 years,

00:09:09.790 --> 00:09:12.090
but you will hear
people calling it vega.

00:09:12.090 --> 00:09:14.580
Obviously, I have probably more
people calling it the vega.

00:09:14.580 --> 00:09:19.300
But anyway, so that's my
first day at Morgan Stanley.

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:21.750
But why did I tell
you the story?

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:24.960
What point I try to make?

00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:29.270
So this story is actually--
when you think about it,

00:09:29.270 --> 00:09:33.970
mathematical or quantitative
finance is a rather new field.

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:37.990
A lot of these terms
were newly introduced.

00:09:37.990 --> 00:09:42.860
And the pricing model
of options, as you know,

00:09:42.860 --> 00:09:47.410
was introduced in the
Black-Scholes in the '70s,

00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:49.830
or some of the ground work
may be done a bit earlier.

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:55.770
But it's not like finance
was a quantitative profession

00:09:55.770 --> 00:09:57.090
to start with.

00:09:57.090 --> 00:09:59.720
So what we witness
in the last 30 years

00:09:59.720 --> 00:10:04.490
was really a transformation of
the trading profession coming

00:10:04.490 --> 00:10:09.320
from mostly
under-educated traders.

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:13.280
Some of them typically joined
the firms in the mail room

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:15.080
and became trader later on.

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:17.360
That's typical career path.

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:20.260
And to nowadays, if you
walk on the trading floor,

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:24.510
you talk to the traders, most
of them have advanced degrees

00:10:24.510 --> 00:10:29.950
and quite a few of them
have very high training

00:10:29.950 --> 00:10:32.580
in mathematics and
computer science.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:36.820
So what has changed over
the last 20 or 30 years?

00:10:36.820 --> 00:10:40.690
I myself, personally, was
probably one of the data

00:10:40.690 --> 00:10:44.370
point experiencing this change.

00:10:44.370 --> 00:10:49.270
And I certainly
didn't expect I would

00:10:49.270 --> 00:10:51.880
be doing this when
I was at MIT, but I

00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:55.990
did that in the last 20 years.

00:10:55.990 --> 00:10:59.030
So the point I'm
trying to tell you

00:10:59.030 --> 00:11:04.120
is, before you dive into
any details of mathematics

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:11.220
or any concept in finance in
this class, just bear in mind,

00:11:11.220 --> 00:11:16.240
this is a field developed in the
last mostly 30 years, or even

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:17.170
shorter.

00:11:17.170 --> 00:11:19.890
And what you really
need to ask questions

00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:26.790
is-- it's not really is it
right or wrong in mathematics,

00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:28.975
is it right or wrong in physics?

00:11:28.975 --> 00:11:31.920
So, how the concepts
are established

00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:35.110
and defined and verified.

00:11:35.110 --> 00:11:37.170
Because this is a field--
the transformation

00:11:37.170 --> 00:11:42.310
about the participants,
products, models, methodology,

00:11:42.310 --> 00:11:44.400
everything are
changing very rapidly.

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:46.630
Even nowadays, they're
still changing.

00:11:46.630 --> 00:11:51.720
So with that, I will
give you some background

00:11:51.720 --> 00:11:57.160
on how the financial
markets actually started,

00:11:57.160 --> 00:12:03.700
and that's really the history
part of this industry.

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:07.960
So, when we talk about
markets, we know in early days

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:10.430
people need to exchange goods.

00:12:10.430 --> 00:12:11.970
You have something
I don't have, I

00:12:11.970 --> 00:12:15.730
have something you don't
have, so there's exchanges.

00:12:15.730 --> 00:12:17.500
Then it becomes centralized.

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:20.530
There are stock exchanges,
futures exchanges all

00:12:20.530 --> 00:12:22.940
over the world where
these products will

00:12:22.940 --> 00:12:27.310
be listed as securities
on these exchanges.

00:12:27.310 --> 00:12:30.560
That's one way of trading,
which is centralized.

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:32.680
Obviously, in the
last 10, 15 years,

00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:37.010
now we have ECNs,
electronic platforms.

00:12:37.010 --> 00:12:41.270
Trade over-- you know, even
larger volume of those trades.

00:12:41.270 --> 00:12:47.070
So, financial products is
really just one form of trading.

00:12:47.070 --> 00:12:52.070
There are many other ways of
trading aside from exchanges.

00:12:52.070 --> 00:12:55.650
One of them, which
is called OTC,

00:12:55.650 --> 00:13:00.600
is over-the-counter, meaning
two counterparties agree

00:13:00.600 --> 00:13:05.920
to do a trade without really
subject to the exchange rules,

00:13:05.920 --> 00:13:09.580
or the underlying trading
agreement does not

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:13.640
have to be a securitized
product, or standardized,

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:16.390
or whatever ways you define it.

00:13:16.390 --> 00:13:18.770
And the different regions
have different exchanges

00:13:18.770 --> 00:13:20.730
and markets, as well.

00:13:20.730 --> 00:13:25.160
And they typically specialize
in local products, local company

00:13:25.160 --> 00:13:31.900
stocks, local bonds,
and local currencies.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:33.910
So, there are many
different forms.

00:13:33.910 --> 00:13:37.780
So again, what's in common?

00:13:37.780 --> 00:13:39.650
That's the question
you need to ask.

00:13:39.650 --> 00:13:42.350
Also, you don't
know the specifics.

00:13:42.350 --> 00:13:47.280
And the currencies, money
itself, are also traded.

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:50.490
And that's where
different currencies

00:13:50.490 --> 00:13:52.510
issued by different countries.

00:13:52.510 --> 00:13:54.810
So, when we talk
about trading stocks--

00:13:54.810 --> 00:13:57.750
there are also people
trade baskets of stocks,

00:13:57.750 --> 00:14:00.300
trade groups of stocks
together, and that's

00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:03.720
stock index or indices.

00:14:03.720 --> 00:14:06.090
So, there are
different products.

00:14:06.090 --> 00:14:09.170
How the stock get listed
on the stock exchange?

00:14:09.170 --> 00:14:13.210
It goes through IPO-- Initial
Public Offering process.

00:14:13.210 --> 00:14:17.340
So, when a company changes
from private to public,

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:19.490
it goes through
this IPO process.

00:14:19.490 --> 00:14:23.160
It's called primary
market, primary listing.

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:28.240
And once the stock is
listed on the exchange

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:30.800
and it becomes
traded in the market,

00:14:30.800 --> 00:14:32.420
we call it secondary trading.

00:14:32.420 --> 00:14:36.270
So, that's after
the primary market.

00:14:36.270 --> 00:14:40.840
And equity or stock
is one form of trading

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:43.670
or one form of
financial products.

00:14:43.670 --> 00:14:45.500
What are other forms?

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:46.520
Loans.

00:14:46.520 --> 00:14:52.110
Actually, debt products are more
generic than equity products.

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:55.700
When you started
thinking about it,

00:14:55.700 --> 00:14:57.430
what is really finance is about?

00:14:57.430 --> 00:15:01.560
It's really about someone
has money, someone doesn't.

00:15:01.560 --> 00:15:05.480
Someone has money to lend out,
someone needs to borrow money.

00:15:05.480 --> 00:15:07.220
So, that's loan.

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:09.490
Loan is really a
private agreement

00:15:09.490 --> 00:15:13.140
between two counterparties
or multiple counterparties.

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:16.610
When you securitize
them, they become bonds.

00:15:16.610 --> 00:15:20.370
And when you look at
bonds, every government

00:15:20.370 --> 00:15:22.830
will issue large sovereign debt.

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:27.660
So, US government has large
outstanding US Treasury debt--

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:29.890
bonds, notes, bills.

00:15:29.890 --> 00:15:34.810
And corporates have issued a
lot of debt product, as well.

00:15:34.810 --> 00:15:37.640
They borrow money when they
need to build a new factory

00:15:37.640 --> 00:15:39.190
or expand.

00:15:39.190 --> 00:15:41.190
Universities borrow money.

00:15:41.190 --> 00:15:45.270
When MIT needs to build a new
building, some of the money

00:15:45.270 --> 00:15:47.640
will come from the
endowment support,

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:52.440
some will come from some
other form of research budget,

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:55.570
or some will come
from debt financing.

00:15:55.570 --> 00:15:58.820
Just borrow from the
public-- local governments,

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:01.370
states, counties, even.

00:16:01.370 --> 00:16:04.510
So, they have various forms.

00:16:04.510 --> 00:16:05.620
So, that's debt product.

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:10.120
Commodities, actually, you know.

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:13.490
Metal, energy,
agriculture products

00:16:13.490 --> 00:16:15.580
are traded, mostly
in the futures

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:17.610
format and some in
physical format,

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:19.350
meaning you take deliveries.

00:16:19.350 --> 00:16:21.590
When you actually
buying and sell,

00:16:21.590 --> 00:16:23.540
you build a warehouse
to take them.

00:16:23.540 --> 00:16:29.870
You ship a tank to
store above the ocean.

00:16:29.870 --> 00:16:33.480
And the real estate, you're
buying and sell houses.

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:36.960
2008 financial crisis,
if you read about it,

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:39.000
this has a lot to do
with the real estate

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:44.580
market, the mortgages, and
asset-backed securities.

00:16:44.580 --> 00:16:46.720
So, I'm not trying to give
you all the definition,

00:16:46.720 --> 00:16:48.130
dumping the information on you.

00:16:48.130 --> 00:16:52.030
But I like you at least
hearing it once today,

00:16:52.030 --> 00:16:56.000
and then you have more interest,
you can read on the side.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:00.220
So asset-backed securities
is when you have an asset,

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:06.150
you basically issue a debt
with the asset backing it.

00:17:06.150 --> 00:17:11.130
And how do you rate
the asset's risk level

00:17:11.130 --> 00:17:14.339
and what's the income
stream, cash flow?

00:17:14.339 --> 00:17:19.089
And before 2008
financial crisis,

00:17:19.089 --> 00:17:25.730
as you heard, large amount
of CMBS-- basically,

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:29.390
it's a commercial
real estate backed

00:17:29.390 --> 00:17:33.730
securities, mortgage securities,
and the residential, as well.

00:17:33.730 --> 00:17:37.180
And further of all of these,
you heard probably a lot

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:39.040
about the derivative products.

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:42.230
So, that started
with swaps, options.

00:17:42.230 --> 00:17:44.460
And the structure
of the products, it

00:17:44.460 --> 00:17:51.320
become more tailor-made for
either investors or borrowers

00:17:51.320 --> 00:17:54.440
to structure the products in
a way to suit their needs.

00:17:54.440 --> 00:17:59.420
And some of the complexity
of those structured products

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:02.730
become quite high,
and the mathematics

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:05.950
involved in pricing them
and the risk management

00:18:05.950 --> 00:18:07.380
become rather challenging.

00:18:14.950 --> 00:18:23.050
So coming back to the
players in the market,

00:18:23.050 --> 00:18:25.850
one large type of
player is really bank.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:34.500
Essentially, after 1933
Glass-Steagall legislation,

00:18:34.500 --> 00:18:36.780
there were two main
types of banks.

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:40.340
One is called commercial bank,
the other is investment bank.

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:43.690
Commercial bank is
supposedly, you're

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:46.680
taking deposits and
lend out the money,

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:51.200
and doing more
commercial services.

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:55.200
Investment bank supposed to
focus on the capital markets,

00:18:55.200 --> 00:19:00.870
raising capital, trading,
and asset management.

00:19:00.870 --> 00:19:08.140
But obviously, after 1999, the
Glass-Steagall was repealed.

00:19:08.140 --> 00:19:10.040
There's no longer that.

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:12.300
Some people blame
that, and probably

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:18.090
for a very good reason, for the
cause of 2008 financial crisis.

00:19:18.090 --> 00:19:22.675
But I want to tell you how
currently investment banks are

00:19:22.675 --> 00:19:23.175
organized.

00:19:25.750 --> 00:19:31.100
Vasily just mentioned he
works in the fixed income.

00:19:31.100 --> 00:19:35.470
So banks typically organized
by institutional business

00:19:35.470 --> 00:19:37.150
and asset management.

00:19:37.150 --> 00:19:40.200
So, within the institutional
client business,

00:19:40.200 --> 00:19:43.590
it has typically
three main parts.

00:19:43.590 --> 00:19:46.540
Fixed income, which
trade the debt

00:19:46.540 --> 00:19:48.990
and the derivative products.

00:19:48.990 --> 00:19:52.850
Equity, trade stocks and
the derivative products.

00:19:52.850 --> 00:19:57.120
And IBD, stands for
Investment Banking Division,

00:19:57.120 --> 00:20:00.240
which really covers
corporate finance,

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:05.290
raising capital, listing
a stock, IPO, and merger

00:20:05.290 --> 00:20:08.370
and acquisition, and advisory.

00:20:08.370 --> 00:20:11.700
So that's how banks
are organized.

00:20:11.700 --> 00:20:16.640
Outside banks, other players,
basically, the asset managers,

00:20:16.640 --> 00:20:19.935
are obviously a very big force
in the financial markets.

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:24.120
So the question a
lot of people ask

00:20:24.120 --> 00:20:27.420
is, is this a zero sum game?

00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:30.420
I'm sure you've heard
this many times.

00:20:30.420 --> 00:20:32.900
So, in the financial
markets, some people win,

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:34.790
some people lose.

00:20:34.790 --> 00:20:38.360
A lot of times, it depends
on the specific products you

00:20:38.360 --> 00:20:40.380
trade, the market you're in.

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:44.950
It is, lot of times,
pretty net zero.

00:20:44.950 --> 00:20:49.280
But why do we need
financial markets?

00:20:49.280 --> 00:20:53.670
This comes back to what
I described before.

00:20:53.670 --> 00:20:55.920
Because something
existed-- actually,

00:20:55.920 --> 00:20:57.250
there's a need for it.

00:20:57.250 --> 00:21:02.310
It's really the need to
bridge between the lenders

00:21:02.310 --> 00:21:03.930
and the borrowers.

00:21:03.930 --> 00:21:07.770
That's really coming down to
the essential relationship.

00:21:07.770 --> 00:21:10.700
So, investors who
have money need

00:21:10.700 --> 00:21:14.260
to have better yield or better
return, better interest.

00:21:14.260 --> 00:21:18.490
In the current environment,
when you have a savings account,

00:21:18.490 --> 00:21:21.240
you don't really
earn much at all.

00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:26.810
And so you would have to take
more risk to generate more

00:21:26.810 --> 00:21:30.400
return, or you
have longer horizon

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:34.620
CDs, other type of products,
or trade the stocks.

00:21:34.620 --> 00:21:37.610
So, when somebody has money,
when you trade stocks,

00:21:37.610 --> 00:21:41.210
you're essentially--
you're buying a stock,

00:21:41.210 --> 00:21:43.060
you give the money somewhere.

00:21:43.060 --> 00:21:45.490
Supposedly, it will
go to the company.

00:21:45.490 --> 00:21:50.400
Company use the money to
generate a better return.

00:21:50.400 --> 00:21:54.580
And for the borrowers,
whoever needs money,

00:21:54.580 --> 00:21:58.030
they need to have
access to the capital.

00:21:58.030 --> 00:22:02.000
So obviously, different
borrowers have different risks.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:04.250
Some people borrow
money, never return.

00:22:04.250 --> 00:22:07.000
So, never generate any
returns, or never even

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:08.690
return the principal.

00:22:08.690 --> 00:22:12.566
And so the trade between
lenders and the borrowers,

00:22:12.566 --> 00:22:15.004
is again, essentially
the main driver

00:22:15.004 --> 00:22:16.045
of the financial markets.

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:24.580
So, a few more words about
the market participants.

00:22:24.580 --> 00:22:30.240
So, banks and so-called dealers
play the role of market making.

00:22:30.240 --> 00:22:32.020
What is market making?

00:22:32.020 --> 00:22:36.930
So, when you or some end
user go to the market,

00:22:36.930 --> 00:22:41.610
wants to buy or sell,
typically, if there's no market,

00:22:41.610 --> 00:22:43.070
you don't really find the match.

00:22:43.070 --> 00:22:46.130
And some of the products
you want to buy or sell

00:22:46.130 --> 00:22:48.810
may not necessarily be liquid.

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:53.050
So, the dealers step in the
middle, make you a price.

00:22:53.050 --> 00:22:55.410
Say, OK, you want
to buy or sell.

00:22:55.410 --> 00:23:00.600
I can tell you-- this
stock, I make you price.

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:08.120
$0.99, and that's my bid.
$0.95, that's my offer.

00:23:08.120 --> 00:23:12.990
So, that's the price I'm
willing to buy or sell.

00:23:12.990 --> 00:23:15.620
But what the result of
the trade-- the dealer

00:23:15.620 --> 00:23:18.140
actually takes the other
side of your trade.

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:21.840
So, they take principal
risk, in this case.

00:23:21.840 --> 00:23:23.630
So, that's the difference
between dealers

00:23:23.630 --> 00:23:24.860
and the brokers.

00:23:24.860 --> 00:23:28.480
So, brokers don't really
take principal risks.

00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:31.650
If you want to buy
something or sell something,

00:23:31.650 --> 00:23:34.980
if I'm a broker, I
don't make you a price.

00:23:34.980 --> 00:23:37.230
I go to the market makers.

00:23:37.230 --> 00:23:40.960
I actually put two
people together,

00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:43.500
matchmaking, make
that trade happen.

00:23:43.500 --> 00:23:44.940
So, I earn the commission.

00:23:44.940 --> 00:23:47.290
So, that's a broker's role.

00:23:47.290 --> 00:23:49.850
So obviously, there are
individual investors,

00:23:49.850 --> 00:23:52.630
retail investors, same meaning.

00:23:52.630 --> 00:23:57.690
Mutual funds, who actually
manage public investors' money,

00:23:57.690 --> 00:24:02.400
typically in the
long-only format.

00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:04.190
Long means you buy something.

00:24:04.190 --> 00:24:09.870
So, you don't really short
sell a particular security.

00:24:09.870 --> 00:24:12.130
Insurance companies
has large asset.

00:24:12.130 --> 00:24:14.410
They need to generate a
return, generate cash flow

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:17.010
to meet their liability needs.

00:24:17.010 --> 00:24:18.870
So, they need to invest.

00:24:18.870 --> 00:24:20.990
And the pension
funds, same thing.

00:24:20.990 --> 00:24:22.650
As inflation goes
higher, they need

00:24:22.650 --> 00:24:26.970
to pay out more to the retirees,
so where do you get the return?

00:24:26.970 --> 00:24:29.440
Sovereign wealth fund,
similarly, endowment

00:24:29.440 --> 00:24:32.740
funds-- they all have
this same situation,

00:24:32.740 --> 00:24:36.360
have capital and needs to deploy
and to make better return.

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:40.750
So this other type of
players, hedge funds.

00:24:40.750 --> 00:24:45.280
So, how many of you
have heard hedge funds?

00:24:45.280 --> 00:24:45.890
OK, good.

00:24:45.890 --> 00:24:48.130
Almost everyone.

00:24:48.130 --> 00:24:51.610
And Peter mentioned that he
used to work at a hedge fund.

00:24:51.610 --> 00:24:55.490
And so, there are
different types

00:24:55.490 --> 00:24:58.290
of strategies, which I
will dive into a bit more,

00:24:58.290 --> 00:25:02.570
but hedge fund play the role
in the market-- they basically

00:25:02.570 --> 00:25:08.380
find opportunities to profit
from inefficient market

00:25:08.380 --> 00:25:13.200
positioning or pricing, so
they have different strategies.

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:16.790
And the private equity is
different type of funds.

00:25:16.790 --> 00:25:22.190
They basically look
to invest in companies

00:25:22.190 --> 00:25:29.140
and either take them private or
invest in a private equity form

00:25:29.140 --> 00:25:33.130
to hopefully improve the
company's profitability,

00:25:33.130 --> 00:25:35.550
and then catch up.

00:25:35.550 --> 00:25:40.430
And governments obviously have
a huge impact on the market.

00:25:40.430 --> 00:25:45.410
So, we know in the financial
crisis, government intervened.

00:25:45.410 --> 00:25:49.160
And not only that, at the
normal market condition,

00:25:49.160 --> 00:25:52.510
government always have a very
large impact on the market,

00:25:52.510 --> 00:25:54.360
because they are
the policymakers.

00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:57.530
They decide the interest
rate and interest rate curve.

00:25:57.530 --> 00:26:01.500
And the different policies
they push out, obviously,

00:26:01.500 --> 00:26:05.630
will generate different
outlook for the future markets,

00:26:05.630 --> 00:26:07.594
therefore, profitability.

00:26:07.594 --> 00:26:09.510
Then the corporate hedges
and the liabilities.

00:26:09.510 --> 00:26:13.170
When corporates borrow
money, they create some risk,

00:26:13.170 --> 00:26:16.280
so they need to be sensitive
to the market, it changes.

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:25.230
So, to summarize the
types of trading.

00:26:25.230 --> 00:26:28.560
The first type is
really just hedging.

00:26:28.560 --> 00:26:30.450
That means you're
not proactively

00:26:30.450 --> 00:26:33.080
adding risk to what you have.

00:26:33.080 --> 00:26:34.615
You already have some exposure.

00:26:37.930 --> 00:26:39.202
Just give you an example.

00:26:39.202 --> 00:26:41.160
Let's say you borrow
money, you bought a house,

00:26:41.160 --> 00:26:44.090
so you have mortgage.

00:26:44.090 --> 00:26:51.490
So, let's say it's a floating
rate mortgage payments.

00:26:51.490 --> 00:26:55.210
And you're worried about
interest rates going higher,

00:26:55.210 --> 00:26:59.600
so you can lock that rate in
into the fixed rate format.

00:26:59.600 --> 00:27:03.770
Or you can find ways
to hedge your exposure.

00:27:03.770 --> 00:27:09.170
Or your corporate has a large
income coming from Europe.

00:27:09.170 --> 00:27:12.950
So, you have euros coming
in, but you're not sure

00:27:12.950 --> 00:27:17.410
if euro would trade stronger
to the US dollar in the future,

00:27:17.410 --> 00:27:19.870
or trade weaker.

00:27:19.870 --> 00:27:22.150
If you think it will be
stronger, you just leave it.

00:27:22.150 --> 00:27:25.020
But if you think it
will trade weaker,

00:27:25.020 --> 00:27:26.535
so you may want to
hedge it, meaning

00:27:26.535 --> 00:27:30.790
you want to sell euro
and buy US dollars.

00:27:30.790 --> 00:27:32.560
And so that's the hedging type.

00:27:32.560 --> 00:27:35.650
The second type, as I
mentioned, is a market maker.

00:27:35.650 --> 00:27:38.770
So, market maker also
takes principal risk,

00:27:38.770 --> 00:27:44.190
but the main source of profit
is really to earn the bid offer.

00:27:44.190 --> 00:27:48.300
I gave you the example
$0.90 bid, $0.95 offer.

00:27:48.300 --> 00:27:53.030
So, that's what the market
maker is trying to profit from.

00:27:53.030 --> 00:27:55.620
But obviously, they
have residual risks

00:27:55.620 --> 00:27:56.620
sitting on the book.

00:27:56.620 --> 00:27:59.090
Not every trade is matched.

00:27:59.090 --> 00:28:03.760
So, how to optimize
those group of trades,

00:28:03.760 --> 00:28:06.420
that's what market
maker is doing.

00:28:06.420 --> 00:28:08.900
Most of the bank's
dealers are market makers.

00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:14.290
In the new regulation,
obviously, proprietary trading

00:28:14.290 --> 00:28:18.260
is banned, right?

00:28:18.260 --> 00:28:21.510
And so the third type is
really the proprietary trader,

00:28:21.510 --> 00:28:23.350
the risk taker.

00:28:23.350 --> 00:28:27.020
So, these are the hedge funds
or some portfolio managers.

00:28:27.020 --> 00:28:33.180
They need to focus on generating
return and control the risk.

00:28:33.180 --> 00:28:37.240
So, that's where the beta and
alpha, the concept comes in.

00:28:37.240 --> 00:28:41.455
So, if you're a portfolio
manager, some people say,

00:28:41.455 --> 00:28:42.020
don't worry.

00:28:42.020 --> 00:28:43.360
Don't go pick any stocks.

00:28:43.360 --> 00:28:46.340
Just buy S&P 500 index fund.

00:28:46.340 --> 00:28:47.280
Very cheap.

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:50.560
You can pay very
little cost to do it.

00:28:50.560 --> 00:28:52.080
That's true.

00:28:52.080 --> 00:28:55.210
But if you want to
beat the S&P 500

00:28:55.210 --> 00:29:03.750
index-- let's assume we call
S&P 500 index fund is asset b.

00:29:03.750 --> 00:29:05.640
So, the return of that, R(b).

00:29:05.640 --> 00:29:08.370
That's a return of that index.

00:29:08.370 --> 00:29:11.868
Now, you have a portfolio a.

00:29:11.868 --> 00:29:16.000
Your time series of
return of your asset a,

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:18.960
obviously, you can
do linear regression.

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:21.150
A lot of you are
math major here,

00:29:21.150 --> 00:29:26.900
and you can find a correlation
between those two time series.

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:31.730
So, how the two returns are
related in a simplified form.

00:29:31.730 --> 00:29:35.270
So you can say, this
actually-- somehow it came out.

00:29:35.270 --> 00:29:37.240
It's supposed to
be alpha and beta,

00:29:37.240 --> 00:29:41.950
but it turned out
to be the letters.

00:29:41.950 --> 00:29:45.760
So, in a short description,
beta is really-- just

00:29:45.760 --> 00:29:50.950
think as correlated move
with the other asset.

00:29:50.950 --> 00:29:56.340
Alpha is really the
difference in the return.

00:29:56.340 --> 00:29:57.060
It's a format.

00:29:57.060 --> 00:30:00.640
You want to beat S&P 500,
so you want to basically

00:30:00.640 --> 00:30:02.720
have certain tracking
of this index,

00:30:02.720 --> 00:30:05.038
but you want to return
more on top of that.

00:30:10.750 --> 00:30:13.960
So let me just go
in bit of details

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:18.000
of how each type of
trade actually occurs.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:20.030
So, when we talk
about hedging, I

00:30:20.030 --> 00:30:21.460
mentioned the currency example.

00:30:21.460 --> 00:30:23.340
Let me give you another example.

00:30:23.340 --> 00:30:27.270
There are a lot of people
issue bonds, or issue debt.

00:30:27.270 --> 00:30:29.680
So this example I'm
going to give you is,

00:30:29.680 --> 00:30:34.060
let's think about
Australian corporate.

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:36.620
Because interest
rate in Australia

00:30:36.620 --> 00:30:40.390
is higher than in
Japan, so typically,

00:30:40.390 --> 00:30:44.730
people like to borrow
money in Japan, because you

00:30:44.730 --> 00:30:47.250
pay smaller interest.

00:30:47.250 --> 00:30:49.670
And they invest it in Australia.

00:30:49.670 --> 00:30:54.190
You earn higher interest rate.

00:30:54.190 --> 00:30:57.350
So let me ask you a question.

00:30:57.350 --> 00:30:59.000
Who can tell me,
why don't people

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:02.030
just do that all day long,
just borrow from Japan

00:31:02.030 --> 00:31:05.720
and invest it in Australia?

00:31:05.720 --> 00:31:08.250
Then that interest
rate, I'm giving you

00:31:08.250 --> 00:31:15.030
example of a difference is about
3.5% for the roughly 10 year

00:31:15.030 --> 00:31:17.135
swap rates.

00:31:17.135 --> 00:31:17.760
Yeah, go ahead.

00:31:17.760 --> 00:31:19.900
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:19.900 --> 00:31:21.060
JAKE XIA: Right.

00:31:21.060 --> 00:31:22.800
Because you invest
in the Australia

00:31:22.800 --> 00:31:24.110
Ozzie, Australian dollar.

00:31:24.110 --> 00:31:27.540
The Australian dollar may
become weaker to the yen.

00:31:27.540 --> 00:31:30.860
You may lose all your
profit, or even more.

00:31:30.860 --> 00:31:35.290
And further, if everybody
plays the same game, then

00:31:35.290 --> 00:31:39.510
when you try to exit, you
have the adverse impact

00:31:39.510 --> 00:31:41.050
of your trade.

00:31:41.050 --> 00:31:44.690
So, let's say you think that's
the right time to do it,

00:31:44.690 --> 00:31:47.190
but then at one
time, you wake up,

00:31:47.190 --> 00:31:49.450
you said, huh, I think too
many people are doing this.

00:31:49.450 --> 00:31:50.850
I want to hedge myself.

00:31:50.850 --> 00:31:51.822
So, what do you do?

00:31:51.822 --> 00:31:52.738
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:31:55.047 --> 00:31:55.630
JAKE XIA: Yep.

00:31:55.630 --> 00:31:57.120
So, you try to lock in, right?

00:31:57.120 --> 00:32:00.920
So basically, you sell
the Australian dollars,

00:32:00.920 --> 00:32:02.980
buy the Japanese yen.

00:32:02.980 --> 00:32:04.900
Or on the interest
rate terms, you

00:32:04.900 --> 00:32:09.970
say you'll basically pay the
Australian dollar in the swap

00:32:09.970 --> 00:32:11.850
leg, and receive yen.

00:32:14.940 --> 00:32:19.760
This involves foreign exchange
trade, interest rate swap,

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:21.860
and the cross-currency swap.

00:32:21.860 --> 00:32:26.130
So, your answer about currency
forward is roughly right,

00:32:26.130 --> 00:32:31.290
but obviously involves a bit
more in actual execution.

00:32:31.290 --> 00:32:32.790
So that's just to
give you example.

00:32:32.790 --> 00:32:35.340
Even if you are
not a finance guy,

00:32:35.340 --> 00:32:39.390
you work in a corporate, you
just do you import, export,

00:32:39.390 --> 00:32:43.440
or building a factory, you
have to know, actually,

00:32:43.440 --> 00:32:44.880
what the exposure is.

00:32:44.880 --> 00:32:49.180
So, risk management, nowadays,
becomes pretty widespread

00:32:49.180 --> 00:32:50.240
responsibility.

00:32:50.240 --> 00:32:55.310
It's not just the corporate
treasury's responsibility.

00:32:55.310 --> 00:32:56.860
So, that's on the hedging side.

00:32:56.860 --> 00:33:01.930
Obviously, if you are
Intel, for example,

00:33:01.930 --> 00:33:05.920
you sell a lot of
chips overseas.

00:33:05.920 --> 00:33:07.660
And your income--
actually, Intel does

00:33:07.660 --> 00:33:11.790
have lot of overseas income
sitting outside the States.

00:33:11.790 --> 00:33:16.570
So, the exposure to them is if
the exchange rate fluctuates,

00:33:16.570 --> 00:33:20.330
dollar becomes a lot stronger,
they actually lose money.

00:33:20.330 --> 00:33:24.590
So, they need to think about how
to hedge the revenue produced

00:33:24.590 --> 00:33:26.660
overseas.

00:33:26.660 --> 00:33:30.080
And obviously, for
import-exporters,

00:33:30.080 --> 00:33:32.250
that's even more apparent.

00:33:32.250 --> 00:33:36.350
And if you're entering
in a merger deal,

00:33:36.350 --> 00:33:38.670
and one company
is buying another,

00:33:38.670 --> 00:33:41.400
you need to hedge your
potential currency

00:33:41.400 --> 00:33:44.250
exposure and your
interest rate exposure.

00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:48.315
And whatever is on the
assets, or the liability,

00:33:48.315 --> 00:33:50.565
or the balance sheet, you
need to hedge your exposure.

00:33:56.080 --> 00:33:58.450
So we talked about
hedging activity.

00:33:58.450 --> 00:34:01.390
Let's talk about market making.

00:34:01.390 --> 00:34:05.010
So if it's a simple
transparent product,

00:34:05.010 --> 00:34:07.320
everybody pretty much
knows where the price is.

00:34:07.320 --> 00:34:10.480
So, if you buy Apple stock,
I think a lot of people

00:34:10.480 --> 00:34:12.179
know pretty much where it is.

00:34:12.179 --> 00:34:15.389
You may even have it
on your cellphone,

00:34:15.389 --> 00:34:18.250
know where that stock is.

00:34:18.250 --> 00:34:21.960
But if it's not transparent,
so what do you do?

00:34:21.960 --> 00:34:24.150
So, if instead of asking
you where Apple is,

00:34:24.150 --> 00:34:26.129
probably you're going
to tell me $495 today.

00:34:26.129 --> 00:34:27.378
AUDIENCE: I don't really know.

00:34:27.378 --> 00:34:28.590
JAKE XIA: OK.

00:34:28.590 --> 00:34:31.870
But if I asked you instead,
what is the call option

00:34:31.870 --> 00:34:37.199
on Apple stock in
two month's time?

00:34:37.199 --> 00:34:40.159
I'll give you a
strike, let's say, 500.

00:34:40.159 --> 00:34:41.790
So you're probably
less transparent.

00:34:41.790 --> 00:34:46.860
So that market maker comes
in to provide that liquidity,

00:34:46.860 --> 00:34:48.440
and then takes the risk.

00:34:48.440 --> 00:34:52.650
They manage the book by
balancing those Greeks, which

00:34:52.650 --> 00:34:53.929
I mentioned earlier.

00:34:53.929 --> 00:34:59.540
Delta, which describes the
[INAUDIBLE] relationship

00:34:59.540 --> 00:35:02.440
of this whole book to the
underlying stock, or underlying

00:35:02.440 --> 00:35:03.700
whatever currency.

00:35:03.700 --> 00:35:05.180
That's called delta.

00:35:05.180 --> 00:35:11.220
Gamma is really the
change of the portfolio.

00:35:11.220 --> 00:35:14.920
Take the derivative
to the delta,

00:35:14.920 --> 00:35:16.490
or to the underlying spot.

00:35:16.490 --> 00:35:20.230
So, that's second-order
derivative.

00:35:20.230 --> 00:35:21.430
Delta is the first order.

00:35:21.430 --> 00:35:27.570
So gamma, now you have curvature
or convexity coming in.

00:35:27.570 --> 00:35:32.180
And theta is really-- nothing
changes in the market.

00:35:32.180 --> 00:35:34.130
Nothing changes
in your position.

00:35:34.130 --> 00:35:39.280
How your trading book is
carrying or bleeding away

00:35:39.280 --> 00:35:40.690
money.

00:35:40.690 --> 00:35:44.120
And we talk about the
volatility exposure was vega.

00:35:44.120 --> 00:35:47.450
And on top of that,
what are the tail risks?

00:35:47.450 --> 00:35:52.030
What are the events can actually
get you into big trouble?

00:35:52.030 --> 00:35:54.330
So people use value at risk.

00:35:54.330 --> 00:35:56.680
So you will hear
this "VaR" concept

00:35:56.680 --> 00:35:59.650
in some of the lectures,
which is also, obviously,

00:35:59.650 --> 00:36:01.150
a very important concept.

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:03.900
I think Peter will-- or
Choongbum will-- probably

00:36:03.900 --> 00:36:06.340
Peter will teach.

00:36:06.340 --> 00:36:09.570
Then capital.

00:36:09.570 --> 00:36:11.220
How much capital are you using?

00:36:11.220 --> 00:36:13.860
It becomes a very
important issue nowadays.

00:36:13.860 --> 00:36:16.520
And balance sheet.

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:18.760
Again, you have asset,
you have liability.

00:36:18.760 --> 00:36:19.770
How do you leverage?

00:36:19.770 --> 00:36:21.290
How much leverage you have?

00:36:21.290 --> 00:36:24.140
Before the crisis, for example,
lot of the banks leverage up

00:36:24.140 --> 00:36:29.010
40 times, meaning when you
have $1, you had $40 exposure.

00:36:29.010 --> 00:36:31.360
So when the market moves
little, you get wiped out.

00:36:31.360 --> 00:36:36.530
That's really what amplified
in the 2008 financial crisis.

00:36:36.530 --> 00:36:40.870
And how do you measure
the asset in balance sheet

00:36:40.870 --> 00:36:43.630
when you have derivatives
rather than a straightforward

00:36:43.630 --> 00:36:44.130
notional?

00:36:50.600 --> 00:36:53.370
So lot of quantitative
type of people

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:56.990
like to focus a bit more
on the risk taking side,

00:36:56.990 --> 00:37:01.120
because people heard stories
about successful cases

00:37:01.120 --> 00:37:03.630
of some hedge funds
using high math.

00:37:03.630 --> 00:37:06.820
They generated very
impressive returns

00:37:06.820 --> 00:37:09.060
and they seem to have an edge.

00:37:09.060 --> 00:37:12.250
So now, people focus
on trading strategies.

00:37:12.250 --> 00:37:17.490
So that falls into the category
of proprietary trading or risk

00:37:17.490 --> 00:37:18.460
taking.

00:37:18.460 --> 00:37:21.300
So that you can just simply
doing directional trading

00:37:21.300 --> 00:37:21.990
strategies.

00:37:21.990 --> 00:37:24.470
Just go long or short the stock.

00:37:24.470 --> 00:37:25.990
That's very simple.

00:37:25.990 --> 00:37:29.530
Those so-called the gut
traders, gut feeling.

00:37:29.530 --> 00:37:30.550
Go with your gut.

00:37:30.550 --> 00:37:31.720
You don't even think.

00:37:31.720 --> 00:37:38.410
You say, I'm eating curry
today, so I go long.

00:37:38.410 --> 00:37:42.310
I'm eating rice
tomorrow, so I go short.

00:37:42.310 --> 00:37:44.400
So, this arbitrage.

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:50.990
Arbitrage is really to find the
relationships between prices,

00:37:50.990 --> 00:37:56.380
and try to profit from those
relationship mispricing.

00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:59.170
This is actually
very interesting.

00:37:59.170 --> 00:38:01.410
Not many people
focus on arbitrage,

00:38:01.410 --> 00:38:04.320
because lot of people
are gut traders.

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:06.230
You essentially just
watch your own market.

00:38:06.230 --> 00:38:07.813
You don't really
care what's going on.

00:38:07.813 --> 00:38:13.740
If you trade gold in the
States, the gold price

00:38:13.740 --> 00:38:17.070
happen in Asia and in
Europe matters, right,

00:38:17.070 --> 00:38:18.760
because you're trading
the same thing.

00:38:18.760 --> 00:38:20.520
If they are not
priced the same way,

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:22.760
you can profit from
the difference.

00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:25.880
And that's just
a simple example.

00:38:25.880 --> 00:38:29.920
But a spot price versus
forward price, that's

00:38:29.920 --> 00:38:31.610
a deterministic relationship.

00:38:31.610 --> 00:38:33.300
It's a mathematical
relationship.

00:38:33.300 --> 00:38:36.050
If that relationship breaks
down, you can also profit.

00:38:36.050 --> 00:38:40.080
So there are many examples
mathematical relationship

00:38:40.080 --> 00:38:44.010
which gives you the
arbitrage opportunity.

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:47.730
The other type is called a
value trader, or relative

00:38:47.730 --> 00:38:48.850
value strategies.

00:38:51.570 --> 00:38:55.790
Think there's a deterministic,
temporary mathematical

00:38:55.790 --> 00:38:56.900
relationship.

00:38:56.900 --> 00:38:59.190
You look at the longer
term in horizon,

00:38:59.190 --> 00:39:01.610
trying to determine what
is really the underlying

00:39:01.610 --> 00:39:03.910
value of a particular
instrument,

00:39:03.910 --> 00:39:06.820
then trade on the
relative value.

00:39:06.820 --> 00:39:10.950
Obviously, there are successful
value investors out there.

00:39:10.950 --> 00:39:15.500
And the systematic trader
builds computer models.

00:39:15.500 --> 00:39:20.330
One example is trend following,
so just follow the price trend.

00:39:20.330 --> 00:39:25.490
That used to be an effective
strategy for some time,

00:39:25.490 --> 00:39:28.220
but when lot of people
doing the same thing, that

00:39:28.220 --> 00:39:31.750
becomes much less effective.

00:39:31.750 --> 00:39:33.730
Or momentum, same thing.

00:39:33.730 --> 00:39:38.480
Stat arb, finding
statistical relationship

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:42.490
among large number
of stocks, then

00:39:42.490 --> 00:39:46.430
trade at the higher frequency.

00:39:46.430 --> 00:39:48.470
And fundamental
analysis, you're really

00:39:48.470 --> 00:39:50.890
trying to understand what's
going on in the world.

00:39:50.890 --> 00:39:54.090
What is the trade balance?

00:39:54.090 --> 00:39:58.190
What is the earning
potential of a company?

00:39:58.190 --> 00:40:00.220
What's the trade
balance of a country?

00:40:00.220 --> 00:40:01.830
What is a policy change?

00:40:01.830 --> 00:40:03.760
What does it mean
when Federal Reserve

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:08.300
announce they're going to
taper the quantitative easing?

00:40:08.300 --> 00:40:12.890
Why the stock market is sold
off in the last couple months,

00:40:12.890 --> 00:40:17.100
especially why stocks in
India, Brazil, Indonesia,

00:40:17.100 --> 00:40:18.590
sold out more.

00:40:18.590 --> 00:40:19.490
Why is that?

00:40:19.490 --> 00:40:22.850
So it goes through those
fundamental analysis.

00:40:22.850 --> 00:40:25.770
And there are
special situations.

00:40:25.770 --> 00:40:31.500
Some companies are going
through particular difficulties,

00:40:31.500 --> 00:40:33.610
assets are priced very cheaply.

00:40:33.610 --> 00:40:39.290
So, there are firms out there --
you probably heard Bain Capital

00:40:39.290 --> 00:40:42.740
and many others -- where they
focus on these private equity

00:40:42.740 --> 00:40:45.085
and special situation
opportunities.

00:40:49.550 --> 00:40:55.690
So what have all of these
to do with mathematics?

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:58.080
Where does math come in?

00:40:58.080 --> 00:40:59.650
How do you use math?

00:40:59.650 --> 00:41:02.890
So, I want to give you
some aspects of that.

00:41:02.890 --> 00:41:07.300
So from my personal experience,
I joined the market,

00:41:07.300 --> 00:41:09.980
really start to working
on pricing models.

00:41:09.980 --> 00:41:11.500
So, that's the first area.

00:41:11.500 --> 00:41:14.160
So, math is very
effective, because when

00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:19.060
you, your bank,
your corporate, you

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:21.830
want to buy some
financial instruments,

00:41:21.830 --> 00:41:25.540
you have to know
where is the price.

00:41:25.540 --> 00:41:28.400
It's easy to observe
a stock in the market,

00:41:28.400 --> 00:41:31.470
but when it comes to
more complex products,

00:41:31.470 --> 00:41:35.350
they just take one step
forward on the complexity,

00:41:35.350 --> 00:41:36.720
which is the option.

00:41:36.720 --> 00:41:38.490
You have to know how
to price an option.

00:41:38.490 --> 00:41:40.660
So, that's where
the math comes in.

00:41:40.660 --> 00:41:43.450
You actually have to be able
to solve differential equations

00:41:43.450 --> 00:41:47.270
to get a model price,
then you obviously

00:41:47.270 --> 00:41:51.640
adjust to your assumptions
to fit into the market.

00:41:51.640 --> 00:41:57.660
So, pricing model, which Vasily
and many of his colleagues

00:41:57.660 --> 00:42:00.690
can tell you more--
which is very much

00:42:00.690 --> 00:42:03.290
a very interesting
and challenging area.

00:42:03.290 --> 00:42:06.050
How do you price all
these instruments?

00:42:06.050 --> 00:42:09.375
And when I say pricing, it's
not in the narrow definition

00:42:09.375 --> 00:42:11.380
of just coming up
with the price.

00:42:11.380 --> 00:42:13.140
When you build a
pricing model, you also

00:42:13.140 --> 00:42:18.220
generate the risk parameters
of these instruments,

00:42:18.220 --> 00:42:21.020
and how do you risk manage them.

00:42:21.020 --> 00:42:23.010
So, that comes to
the second part.

00:42:23.010 --> 00:42:26.840
So math is very useful
in risk management,

00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:29.600
which I will give you
some -- not quiz --

00:42:29.600 --> 00:42:31.920
questions after this slide.

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:35.610
You can see that risk management
itself is very challenging.

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:37.460
It's not a purely
mathematical question,

00:42:37.460 --> 00:42:40.140
but yet, math plays
a very important role

00:42:40.140 --> 00:42:44.050
to quantify how much
exposure you have.

00:42:44.050 --> 00:42:47.010
Then, the third is
trading strategies.

00:42:47.010 --> 00:42:50.630
Again, I think a lot of
people with math background,

00:42:50.630 --> 00:42:52.660
or in general,
people are looking

00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:57.170
for the so-called holy
grail trading strategies.

00:42:57.170 --> 00:43:00.330
It's almost like perpetual
motion machines people

00:43:00.330 --> 00:43:02.005
looking for 100 years ago.

00:43:02.005 --> 00:43:03.570
You just turn it on.

00:43:03.570 --> 00:43:05.660
It makes money by itself.

00:43:05.660 --> 00:43:08.350
You go to sleep, you go on
vacation, you come back,

00:43:08.350 --> 00:43:10.760
you'll have more in
your bank account.

00:43:10.760 --> 00:43:13.560
Obviously, that's
not going to happen.

00:43:13.560 --> 00:43:20.040
The robotrader, a robotic
trader, is a dream.

00:43:20.040 --> 00:43:26.350
It has its place or its use,
but it's a fast evolving market.

00:43:26.350 --> 00:43:31.440
You have to constantly
either upgrade your research

00:43:31.440 --> 00:43:34.460
and adjust your strategies.

00:43:34.460 --> 00:43:38.380
There's no such thing you
can build and leave it alone,

00:43:38.380 --> 00:43:40.480
it runs for itself forever.

00:43:40.480 --> 00:43:45.030
But I just want to
mention that because maybe

00:43:45.030 --> 00:43:47.100
towards the end of the
term you will feel, hmm,

00:43:47.100 --> 00:43:50.280
I came up with this
brilliant trading strategy.

00:43:50.280 --> 00:43:52.240
I think it's going to
make money forever.

00:43:52.240 --> 00:43:55.785
Please let me know first.

00:43:55.785 --> 00:43:59.260
AUDIENCE: And me second.

00:43:59.260 --> 00:44:04.700
PROFESSOR: So, I want to
leave some time to Vasily.

00:44:04.700 --> 00:44:07.420
Actually, he can give
you some examples

00:44:07.420 --> 00:44:10.400
of projects of last
year's students

00:44:10.400 --> 00:44:16.030
who actually came to this class
and did some real application

00:44:16.030 --> 00:44:17.390
at Morgan Stanley.

00:44:17.390 --> 00:44:20.120
But before I hand
it over to Vasily,

00:44:20.120 --> 00:44:22.050
let me ask you some questions.

00:44:22.050 --> 00:44:25.060
I just want to-- not really
to quiz you, just give you

00:44:25.060 --> 00:44:30.490
the sense how math and
intuition and judgment

00:44:30.490 --> 00:44:32.330
can come into the same place.

00:44:32.330 --> 00:44:35.820
So, let me first give you an
example I call risk aversion.

00:44:35.820 --> 00:44:41.306
So, you are facing two choices,
choice A and a choice B. Choice

00:44:41.306 --> 00:44:45.540
A being you have 80
chance to lose $500.

00:44:45.540 --> 00:44:50.696
You have 20% chance to win $500.

00:44:50.696 --> 00:44:51.820
That's pretty clear, right?

00:44:51.820 --> 00:44:56.780
That's choice A. Or
choice B, you basically

00:44:56.780 --> 00:45:01.960
just lock in you have
100% chance to lose $280.

00:45:01.960 --> 00:45:08.850
Let me ask you, for whoever
likes to choose choice A,

00:45:08.850 --> 00:45:10.154
please raise your hand.

00:45:15.024 --> 00:45:16.980
One, two, three, four.

00:45:16.980 --> 00:45:22.280
About six out of say,
let's call it 50.

00:45:22.280 --> 00:45:25.733
So, can I ask you why you
think choice A makes sense?

00:45:25.733 --> 00:45:27.774
AUDIENCE: So, I know it's
a lower expected value,

00:45:27.774 --> 00:45:35.370
but I enjoy gambling and I would
rather take the chance of--

00:45:35.370 --> 00:45:39.080
JAKE XIA: Right, because you
don't want to lock in that $280

00:45:39.080 --> 00:45:39.900
loss, right?

00:45:39.900 --> 00:45:41.740
That, or you still
have 20% chance to win.

00:45:44.380 --> 00:45:46.250
For the ones raised
their hand for choice A,

00:45:46.250 --> 00:45:48.190
are there any other reasons?

